{
  "schema_version": 2,
  "id": "01KVN657YD2TDH2XBYH1HQ08ZE",
  "title": "LurMotorn — BLE Phase A: the cross-platform transport contract",
  "audience": "The developer building LurMotorn (you)",
  "summary": "Phase A of the BLE link (issue #3) — the pure-C++, hardware-free half: the contract both phones must agree on, proven on the host with zero radio. No Bluetooth, JNI, Kotlin, or Mac here; that is Phase B (Android) and Phase D (iOS).\n\nArchitecture note: LurMotorn is symmetric peer-to-peer — there is NO host and no peer that owns the global source of truth. Authority over state is distributed per-entity to the peer whose player interacts with it most tightly (in chess, each phone owns its own pieces; in a shooter, each phone owns spawning its own units but hands movement-authority of a unit to whoever is shooting at it). Ownership + replication live in Modules/Net, never the transport. The BLE peripheral/central split below is a radio mechanic only and confers no authority; once the link is up it is a symmetric two-way datagram pipe.\n\nWhat Phase A pins down is the shared wire contract both backends compile against, so Android and iOS cannot silently diverge into a wire incompatibility. Everything here builds and unit-tests via build.ps1 and on the macOS CI under Apple's clang.\n\nLexicon\n\n**BLE** — Bluetooth Low Energy; the only serverless link that works between an iPhone and an Android phone, so it is LurMotorn's transport.\n\n**GATT** — Generic Attribute Profile; BLE's data model of services and characteristics that a peripheral exposes and a central reads/writes.\n\n**peripheral** — the device that hosts the GATT server on the radio (advertises the service, owns the characteristic). A transport-layer role ONLY — not a game-state authority.\n\n**central** — the device that scans for and connects to the peripheral on the radio. A transport-layer role ONLY — not a game-state authority.\n\n**characteristic** — a single GATT data endpoint; here one writable + notifiable characteristic is the bidirectional datagram channel.\n\n**advertise / scan** — the peripheral broadcasts its presence; the central listens for it. Discovery is symmetric here: both phones do both.\n\n**UUID** — a 128-bit identifier; our service and characteristic UUIDs are the wire identity both platforms must match exactly.\n\n**ITransport** — the engine's platform-neutral 'move bytes to the peer' interface; BLE and the loopback both implement it.\n\n**datagram** — one self-contained message (already minimal); the transport ships it as-is without re-framing.\n\n**loopback** — an in-process ITransport pair used for host tests: one endpoint's Send is delivered straight to the other's Receiver, no radio.\n\n**role tie-break** — the deterministic rule that hands two symmetric peers opposite GATT *radio* roles (one peripheral, one central) without any negotiation. Radio only — not authority.\n\n**interaction-local authority** — LurMotorn's ownership model: each peer is authoritative for the state its player interacts with most tightly, so that interaction is instant and never round-tripped to a host. Distributed per-entity, lives in Net — not the transport.\n\n**legal-move index** — the codec sends only a move's position in the deterministic legal-move list, not its squares; both phones regenerate the same list and map the index back.\n\n**CTest** — CMake's test runner; each test is a plain executable that exits non-zero on failure.",
