    }
  ],
  "phases": [
    {
      "id": "01KVN657YF4R3RGWPW124TVKA8",
      "title": "The shared contract + host proof",
      "summary": "One header pins the cross-platform wire identity (UUIDs) and the role tie-break; a loopback ITransport lets the host exercise a real datagram round-trip; and the tests prove a chess move survives the trip through the transport seam — issue #3's 'done when', in software.",
      "steps": [
        {
          "id": "01KVN657YH6SHWHP1E51GCEYZN",
          "title": "The wire constants, defined once",
          "code_path": "Modules/Transport/Public/Lur/Transport/BleProtocol.h",
          "line_start": 21,
          "line_end": 32,
          "note": "The service + datagram-characteristic UUIDs and advertised name are defined in ONE header so they can't drift between the Kotlin and Swift backends — pure constant-deduplication, NOT a claim that either peer owns game state. Changing a UUID is a breaking wire change (bump ProtocolVersion).",
          "note_comments": [],
          "code_comments": []
        },
        {
          "id": "01KVN657YKDA11XHGG007M9F93",
          "title": "Opposite roles with no negotiation",
          "code_path": "Modules/Transport/Public/Lur/Transport/BleProtocol.h",
          "line_start": 42,
          "line_end": 44,
          "note": "Both phones advertise AND scan, so both reach this pure function with the two ids swapped. A total order on the ids hands them opposite answers for free — the smaller id hosts the peripheral — so they never both try to be the GATT server. This is a RADIO role only: it decides who advertises vs who connects, nothing about game-state authority. Once connected the channel is a symmetric two-way datagram pipe; authority over state is distributed in the Net layer (interaction-local ownership), never here.",
          "note_comments": [],
          "code_comments": []
        },
        {
          "id": "01KVN657YM8D9AYJZZ2C6FCS0M",
          "title": "Loopback: an ITransport with no radio",
          "code_path": "Modules/Transport/Public/Lur/Transport/Loopback.h",
          "line_start": 17,
          "line_end": 39,
          "note": "Two linked endpoints: whatever one Sends is delivered synchronously to the other's Receiver. Because it satisfies the same ITransport contract the BLE backend will, code tested against this runs unchanged over the real link.",
          "note_comments": [],
          "code_comments": []
        },
        {
          "id": "01KVN657YNTMYRKY5JERHEZRWZ",
          "title": "Test: the tie-break is opposite",
          "code_path": "Modules/Transport/Tests/TransportTests.cpp",
          "line_start": 35,
          "line_end": 45,
          "note": "Two devices reaching the tie-break with swapped ids must pick OPPOSITE roles — exactly one peripheral. This is the cross-platform invariant that keeps the GATT server unambiguous.",
          "note_comments": [],
          "code_comments": []
        },
        {
          "id": "01KVN657YPNM5C3BYBECMJ7KQ7",
          "title": "Test: a real move round-trips over the seam",
          "code_path": "Modules/Transport/Tests/TransportTests.cpp",
          "line_start": 81,
          "line_end": 125,
          "note": "The payoff: encode e2e4 to its legal-move index, ship the byte through the LoopbackTransport, and the receiver decodes it back to the identical move using its OWN regenerated legal list. Squares never travel — only the index does. This is issue #3's 'move codec round-trips over the live link', proven with no hardware.",
          "note_comments": [],
          "code_comments": []
        }
      ],
      "diagrams": [
        {
          "id": "01KVN657YQJZ5CRXNZAGNFCE2R",
          "source": "sequenceDiagram\n  participant S as Sender (Chess)\n  participant TA as Loopback A\n  participant TB as Loopback B\n  participant R as Receiver (Chess)\n  S->>S: GenerateLegalMoves + EncodeMove(e2e4)\n  Note over S: 20 legal -> 5 bits -> 1 byte\n  S->>TA: Send(bytes)\n  TA->>TB: deliver to peer\n  TB->>R: Receiver(bytes)\n  R->>R: GenerateLegalMoves (same position)\n  R->>R: DecodeMove -> e2e4",
          "caption": "The move round-trip the test verifies. Only the move's INDEX in the legal list crosses the transport (one byte); each side reconstructs the full move from its own regenerated legal-move list. Swap the LoopbackTransport for the BLE backend and nothing above the ITransport seam changes."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
